respectively. One-, 3- and 5-year actuarial anastomosis success rates were 
96.7%, 93.3%, and 93.3%, respectively. Successful revision tracheal end-to-end 
anastomosis was performed once, resulting in an overall 96.9% success rate in 
our series. None of the following variables-sex, age, cause for intubation, 
intubation type (laryngotracheal and/or tracheotomy) and duration, delay from 
initial injury, presence of an open stoma, number of tracheal rings resected, 
and type of sutures used-were statistically related to the anastomosis success 
rate or the incidence of complications.

